<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / EC-Greek row over Macedonia worsens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER, KERIN HOPE and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN, ATHENS, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE prospect of a rupture between Greece and her European Community partners
over Macedonia drew closer yesterday after the Danish presidency of the EC
called for the United Nations to resolve the status of the former Yugoslav
republic.
Mr Uffe Ellemann-Jensen, Danish foreign minister, said he believed the UN
Security Council could reach a solution as early as next week, in which case
Denmark was ready to recognise Macedonia.
'We have a black spot on our conscience,' Mr Ellemann-Jensen said in
Copenhagen. 'We have reached the point where we cannot keep the lid on this
(in the EC).
'We have to look to the UN for a solution.'
Greece has held up EC recognition of Yugoslavia for almost a year on the
grounds that it undermines the status of the northern Greek province of
Macedonia. Athens argues that the republic should choose a different name to
avoid implying a territorial claim on Greek Macedonia.
A Community decision to hand the issue over to the UN - thus allowing
individual states to open diplomatic relations - would be viewed in Athens
as a breach of EC solidarity.
The Greek government reacted angrily yesterday to Mr Ellemann-Jensen's
proposal. A Foreign Ministry spokesman said the Danish foreign minister
'should respect Community policy as defined at two EC summits on the
preconditions for recognition'.
Athens is also trying to delay UN recognition for Macedonia by arguing that
the Security Council should be briefed on the Greek position before
considering the republic's request for membership, which was formally
submitted last week.
The Danish foreign minister raised questions about Greece's support for UN
economic sanctions against Serbia. An EC Commission report last year accused
Greek companies of systematic sanctions busting.
Mr Ellemann-Jensen also accused Athens of blocking an EC plan agreed at last
month's summit in Edinburgh to send Ecu50m (Pounds 40.5m) of humanitarian
aid to Macedonia.
However, after a meeting of EC foreign minister in Paris late last night he
said his Greek counterpart had promised to help EC aid reach the former
Yugoslav republic.
Peace reprieve, Page 19
