<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 93 / World markets react calmly to air strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Economics and Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORLD financial markets reacted calmly to the allied attack on Iraq
yesterday, write our Economics and Foreign Staff.
Reports that President George Bush was planning an attack had pushed the
dollar to a high of DM1.6333 in European trading, from a previous close in
London at DM1.632.
White House confirmation of bombing raids lifted the dollar higher in the
US, to DM1.635, before profit-taking brought it back to DM1.6225. In Tokyo,
the dollar opened weaker at DM1.6185, although analysts said the US currency
should benefit from heightened tension, as it was seen as a 'safe haven'.
The Nikkei average was down slightly in early Tokyo trading on concern about
further conflict. US shares retreated on news of the attack, but later
recovered. Having fallen 20 points, the Dow Jones Industrial Average closed
down just 1.08 at 3,263.56. In London, the FT-SE 100 index of leading shares
closed down 12.6 at 2,745.3.
Oil prices were unchanged late yesterday after moving up about 30 cents a
barrel on the immediate news of the attack.
