<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / International Company News: ISMA rules confirmed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission has confirmed the rules of the International
Securities Market Association do not breach EC competition law, the bond
market trade association said yesterday, writes Richard Waters.
The EC 'comfort letter', first sought by ISMA in March 1990, gives the
association limited protection from legal action under EC law, said Mr John
Langton, secretary-general of the association.
ISMA decided to seek the EC's assurance since it is not subject to any
single national regulatory system - although it is a Designated Investment
Exchange in the UK and its rules are reviewed by the UK's Office of Fair
Trading.
Before issuing its letter, the EC last year forced the association to drop
two rules which had restricted inter-dealer brokers in the international
bond markets to dealing only with market-makers, rather than with end
investors.
</TEXT>
