<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Britannia to shed jobs and buy aircraft
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITANNIA Airways, Britain's biggest charter airline, is to spend Pounds
250m on new aircraft and shed 560 jobs in an efficiency drive.
The aircraft order includes a Pounds 40m engine contract with Rolls-Royce.
Britannia, subsidiary of Thomson Holidays, Britain's biggest package tour
operator, will cut 290 jobs in its engineering division and 160 pilots.
Mr Roger Burnell, managing director of Britannia, said some compulsory
redundancies would be inevitable.
The cuts come largely because the company's new fleet will consist of fewer,
larger aircraft. Mr Burnell said: 'By summer 1994 we will have 29 aircraft
compared with 38 in summer 1992. The new aircraft will need less
maintenance, so we will need fewer pilots and engineers.'
Pilots will spend more time flying as a result of a new rostering system and
changes to employment contracts. Extra cabin crew will be taken on.
Britannia, based in Luton, Bedfordshire, is buying five new Boeing 757s from
Boeing in a deal worth Dollars 275m (Pounds 181m). Another two will come
from Los Angeles based International Lease Finance Corporation.
Each 757 will carry up to 235 passengers in an all-economy seating
configuration.
By the summer of 1994, Britannia's fleet will consist entirely of Boeing
757s and the larger, wide-bodied 767s. Both models are capable of flying
across the Atlantic, unlike the shorter-range 737s.
Mr Burnell said the fleet modernisation would increase the capacity of the
airline by about 5 per cent, even though fewer aircraft would be operated.
He said the holiday industry had been little affected by the economic
recession. Britannia's sales last year amounted to about Pounds 550m, 14 per
cent higher than in 1991. Sales this year would be about the same as last
year.
Britannia also announced yesterday that its ground handling operation at
Luton would be taken over by Serviceair. About 35 research jobs in Dorset
will be reprieved in a review of government plans for cutting more than
2,000 staff at the restructured Defence Research Agency.
Closure plans for 15 sites were confirmed in a written Commons reply by Mr
Jonathan Aitken, defence procurement minister. The cuts, which involve
abandoning almost a third of the DRA's sites, are aimed at saving Pounds 90m
a year.
</TEXT>
