<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Share option 'may be failing in aim'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DIRECTORS exercising share options in the second quarter of 1992
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the period spanning the general election - typically realised a gain of 80
per cent, according to Income Data Services, the independent pay research
group.
The study suggests that share options - the right to buy shares in the
company one works for at a future date but at today's prices - may be
failing in their aim of binding directors to their employers over the long
term. The gain may be a paper one if the shares are held, or a real one if
sold.
IDS said: 'Share options are a neglected element of the current corporate
governance debate, but, given that our analysis shows they are a substantial
part of directors' remuneration package, it could be that more attention
should be focused on them.'
The study, based on a sample of 153 share options exercised by directors of
quoted companies in the second quarter of 1992, found that the median cash
gain was Pounds 49,200. For directors of FT-SE 100 companies only, the gain
was Pounds 94,980 - well below the Pounds 142,606 in the last quarter of
1991.
IDS said: 'Every quarter has its own factors which will influence the value
of shares. We have heard arguments which suggest directors who feared a
Labour victory tended to exercise their options ahead of the general
election, and equally some exercising their options after the election when
the market rose. But we have no direct evidence of the effect.'
The study confirmed an earlier IDS options analysis finding that directors
tended to exercise their options after an average of 4 1/2 years - at the
'earliest opportunity'. Options must be held for three years and exercised
within 10.
IDS said, 'Share options were originally devised partly as a long-term
incentive to tie in the behaviour of top directors with their companies. The
study suggests they may not be really working.'
Monthly Review of Salaries and Benefits, Incomes Data Services, Top Pay
Unit, 193 St John Street, London EC1V 4LS. By subscription.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99  Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
