<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Soros dealing nets big profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE New York-based financial group headed by Hungarian financier George
Soros turned in a profit of Dollars 2bn-Dollars 3bn (Pounds 1.3bn-Pounds
1.9bn) last year, one of his top aides said in London yesterday.
Mr Stan Druckenmiller, a managing director of Soros Fund Management, said
'substantially less than half' the profits came from speculation on
sterling. The rest came from dealing in other currencies and financial
instruments.
He denied that the fund management group - in which Mr Soros has a one-third
stake - had contributed to recent tensions over the French franc by selling
the currency. Last week the franc brushed its floor against the D-Mark
within the European exchange rate mechanism, although this week it has
strengthened.
Last summer the fund management group made about Dollars 1bn from selling
sterling before Britain's ERM exit.
Mr Druckenmiller said it was wrong to think his organisation had
specifically targeted the pound for selling. 'Sterling was one piece in the
matrix (of our overall operations).'
While in London, he met Treasury and Bank of England officials for talks
about currency operations, which one official described as 'helpful'.
Soros Fund Management currently owns a portfolio of more than Dollars 7bn.
The total is due to fall over the next few months after profits on last
year's operations are paid to shareholders. Mr Druckenmiller said the franc
was 'not fundamentally overvalued' in the ERM and that Soros Fund Management
'had no plans' to sell it.
'If the ERM did not exist and the franc no longer had a peg to the D-Mark
then in our view the franc would not depreciate,' he said.
</TEXT>
