<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Expert scoffs at US fears of long-term decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS THAT the US is in long-term economic decline relative to other nations
are totally unfounded, according to Mr Michael Boskin, outgoing chairman of
the Council of Economic Advisers.
'Declinists' have got their facts wrong, Mr Boskin asserts in his annual
Economic Report of the President, released today. Far from
deindustrialising, the US has been gaining ground on other leading
economies.
The report says the US share of the total industrial output of the 24
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development member states is
higher today than in 1970. US exports have risen from 8 to 11 per cent of
gross domestic product in the past five years, confirming that the US is
'internationally more competitive' than it has been for decades.
The US still has the highest standard of living, as measured by per capita
GDP, and the highest level of industrial productivity, the report says.
Looking forward, Mr Boskin projects a substantial improvement in US
productivity growth.
Output per hour in non-farm businesses will grow at an annual rate of 1.4
per cent between 1990 and 1998, compared with 0.6 per cent and 0.8 per cent
registered in the 1970 and 1980 business cycles, although slower than in the
immediate post-war dec-ades.
The likely increase in productivity growth will reflect a more experienced
labour force as the 'baby boom' generation matures and higher levels of
investment brought about primarily by lower interest rates and inflation.
Mr Boskin concedes, however, that serious problems remain, including the
'deplorable' quality of secondary education, an excessively costly health
care system that fails to insure many Americans, and continuing high levels
of poverty.
</TEXT>
