<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Rover faces EC fine over discounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROVER may be fined by the European Commission for restricting the discounts
some of its dealers could offer customers in 1989 and 1990.
The British car maker has offered to pay compensation.
The restriction breaches EC competition policy and could lead to prosecution
under Article 85 of the Treaty of Rome.
However, the Commission said yesterday no formal charges had yet been
brought against Rover over the discount restrictions. It therefore dismissed
suggestions that Rover could be facing a fine of Pounds 2.5m and a bill for
compensation of up to Pounds 65m.
The British Aerospace subsidiary is already involved in another dispute with
the Commission, which wants repayment of Pounds 44.4m government aid granted
to BAe when it bought Rover in 1988.
Rover Group refused to comment on the discounts issue yesterday. But it does
not dispute that the restrictions occurred. It has offered compensation of
Pounds 500,000 but this so far has proved unacceptable to the Commission.
Rover's case is that the restrictions were imposed between late 1989 and
early 1990 by several UK regional offices which were unaware they breached
EC rules; that they were imposed without the knowledge of Rover's board;
that they affected relatively few transactions; and that they were stopped
as soon as the board became aware of them.
The Commission acknowl-edges that Rover itself brought the matter to
Brussels' attention in 1990.
Whether the Commission does decide to institute proceedings is expected to
depend on the outcome of discussions over compensation.
The Commission cannot compel Rover to pay compensation, but an offer from
the car company which it regarded as inadequate could have a strong bearing
on the size of any fine it might impose.
Any decision on proceedings will be in the hands of Mr Karel Van Miert, Sir
Leon Brittan's successor as competition commissioner.
Mr Van Miert will also decide when and if there is to be further EC action
to make BAe repay the Pounds 44.4m government 'sweeteners' for BAe to take
over Rover in 1988.
</TEXT>
