<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Adequate safety requirements for BR
train operators after privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS to privatise British Rail will increase the number and severity of
railway accidents unless adequate safety requirements are imposed on train
operators, the Health and Safety Executive warned in a report published
yesterday, John Willman writes.
The HSE, the independent, government-funded safety watchdog, said that
current safety standards on the UK railways were high but could be raised
further. But maintaining current standards depended on the close integration
of BR's operations, which privatisation will split between many different
organisations.
'Companies with little or no previous experience of operating on the railway
and managers with limited experience of railway safety issues will enter the
industry,' the HSE said.
New controls will be needed to curb the risk of accidents, the HSE said. The
list of 38 recommendations - all accepted by the government - includes a
mass of new regulations covering matters such as the transport of dangerous
substances by rail and the assesment of the competence of train drivers.
</TEXT>
