<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: MPs rap Maxwell lawyers over cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMMONS social security committee yesterday harshly criticised the
lawyers and accountants responsible for recovering assets stolen from the
pension funds of the late Robert Maxwell and urged that no further
government funds be spent on pensioners until the advisers distributed the
funds they had collected.
Mr Frank Field MP, the Labour chairman, said: 'We are anxious that the
government does not increase (funding) further or the whole wretched process
will drag on for another year.'
The committee released a report on its hearings into the operation to
recover more than Pounds 440m stolen from the pension funds. Administrators
to the various pension schemes are disputing each other's claims to some of
the assets recovered, preventing them from being paid to pensioners.
The MPs recommended that Sir John Cuckney, who is heading a
government-sponsored trust raising voluntary contributions from City
institutions, be appointed to act as mediator among the various parties and
set a six-month deadline for the parties to reach agreement.
The Department of Social Security called the report 'timely' and said
ministers had already expressed concern about the delay in returning funds
to the Maxwell Pension Schemes.
A Pounds 2.5m government 'drip feed' allocated to pay pensions last year is
shortly to be exhausted.
Mr Field said that in the past year, almost none of the Pounds 150m
recovered on behalf of pensioners had been distributed. In that time, Pounds
34.1m had been spent on solicitors, accountants and others charged with
recovering money. That sum might rise to Pounds 100m, he said.
The committee singled out for special criticism Mr Peter Phillips, partner
at Buchler Phillips and joint receiver to the estate of Mr Maxwell, whom it
accused of needlessly pursuing 'claims to property of a fanciful nature'.
Mr Field said the committee was drawing up a schedule of representatives of
investment banks, including Credit Suisse, Lehman Brothers, Bank of America,
Capel-Cure Myers and Invesco MIM to question how those banks came to be in
receipt of pension fund assets.
The banks had claimed they had received the assets in good faith as
collateral for loans to Mr Maxwell. Mr Field said that refunds to the
pension schemes might be forthcoming after those hearings.
</TEXT>
