<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: BR sell-off may take a decade -
Proposals for railway safety arrangements and pension provisions outlined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John MacGregor announced more details of the government's rail
privatisation proposals yesterday, while appearing to acknowledge for the
first time that the process might take at least a decade to complete.
Using a Labour-initiated debate to refute recent charges of a rail
privatisation U-turn, the transport secretary undertook to implement all 38
recommendations in a Health and Safety Commission report published
yesterday, examining the safety implications of the government's plans.
Mr MacGregor also announced proposals for a joint industry pension scheme
for rail workers to succeed the British Rail arrangement.
He said: 'There is not a shred of a policy that is dead and buried and not a
shred of a U-turn in this.'
But in responding to taunts from Labour backbenchers of 'twelve years',
relating to the expected time frame of the recently announced German rail
privatisation, Mr MacGregor seemed to concede that reform of the railways in
Britain would also be a slow process.
'Our timescale to complete our whole privatisation process will be about the
same,' he replied.
The transport secretary declined Labour's invitation to give an assurance
that no lines would be closed as the proposed reforms took effect.
Mr MacGregor said BR's existing safety organisation would be maintained as a
unit and transferred to Railtrack, the proposed track authority. He said
Railtrack would also be responsible for providing a national timetable.
He said the planned joint pensions scheme should not be compulsory for
future industry employers for all time but future pension benefits should be
no less favourable than in the present scheme.
The portion of the current fund relating to railway pensioners would either
be set aside and administered separately with no guarantee as to future
benefit levels or taken over by the government, which would undertake to pay
index-linked pensions.
He undertook to publish the main privatisation bill 'just as soon as' the
paving legislation secured royal assent 'which I hope will be very soon.'
Mr Robert Adley, Tory chairman of the cross-party transport select
committee, criticised the government's plans on a number of counts, claiming
the bill was on 'a political timetable based on purely electoral
considerations.
He urged a plan which would end the freight monopoly, then the passenger
monopoly, then create integrated railway companies, and introduce private
sector capital and management, if appropriate.
A buoyant Mr John Prescott, shadow transport secretary, opened proceedings
for Labour said privatisation would mean the doubling of fares.
The issue at stake was not ownership but the modernisation of the rail
system, he said, warning that the cost of the new bureaucracy would be paid
by sacking 'professional railwaymen desperately trying to provide a
service.'
A Labour motion opposing rail privatisation fell by 309 votes to 270, a
majority of 39.
</TEXT>
