<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: New regulations on 'policy' adverts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ADVERTISING by central government and local authorities will for the first
time be subject to a self-regulatory code of practice, the Advertising
Standards Authority said yesterday.
Regulations covering the advertising industry will be expanded to include
public policy statements, but the ASA has stopped short of scrutinising
'advertisements whose principal function is party-political' for honesty and
truthfulness.
The decision was criticised yesterday by the Labour party and the Trades
Union Congress. Mr David Hill, Labour's director of communications, said the
code should cover advertising such as the Conservative campaign during last
year's general election which highlighted what it called Labour's 'tax
bombshell'.
The TUC, which drew up a submission for the revised code, said the new rules
were 'inconsistent'.
Sir Timothy Raison, chairman of the ASA, said yesterday it had decided to
exclude direct party political advertising from the code of practice
because:
Political parties are involved in appealing to the electorate and Sir
Timothy questioned whether the ASA should 'have the right to judge those
appeals'.
There was already scope for a right of reply by opposing parties.
The practicalities of the political arena would make it difficult for the
ASA to intervene with sufficient speed.
Mr Richard Wade, outgoing director-general of the Advertising Association
and chairman of the ASA committee that drew up the extended code, said
yesterday: 'We started out by wanting all political advertising brought
within the code, but came to the view that party political advertisements
are different in kind.'
Advertisements promoting government policy - such as those from the Central
Office of Information, one of the UK's largest-spending advertisers - will
fall under the new rules.
The expanded regulations, which come into effect on April 15, will also
cover charities, lobbying groups, trade unions and other advertisers
expressing opinions on issues in the public domain. Previously, the code
excluded such advertising unless it made a direct appeal for funds.
Advertising claims made by non-commercial bodies will now have to be
supported by documentary evidence to back up facts, figures and assertions
used in support of their causes.
</TEXT>
