<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Part-time work for managers increasing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PART-time work is making inroads into managerial jobs and seven out of 10
private-sector companies have at least one part-time manager, according to a
survey published yesterday by the Chartered Institute of Management
Accountants.
Part-time work has traditionally been concentrated in junior service-sector
jobs. Of the 5.7m part-timers in the UK, only 2.3 per cent (136,000 people)
are classified as managers. If public-sector professionals (mainly teachers)
are included, the proportion rises to 7.6 per cent, still low compared with
some Continental countries.
The survey of more than 100 companies found that the trend is growing,
especially among women managers with children in service-sector businesses
in the south-east. The survey says employers have found that productivity
gains and savings from the retention of trained staff makes employment of
flexible managers a 'good deal' for them.
It also finds plenty of scope for more part-time work among managers, but
warns that part-timers are less likely to be promoted. Job sharing, where
two managers share responsibilities, is comparatively rare. Most employers
and managers prefer individuals in self-contained jobs to work between two
and four days a week.
Two and three-day patterns are more common in retailing, while general
services financial services and hotels use part-time managers most.
There are more than twice as many women part-time managers as men, with most
men concentrated in the 65-69 age group and in the financial services
sector. Many women do not have children - 54,000, compared with 76,000 who
do.
</TEXT>
