<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / House price fall accelerates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSE prices fell 4.3 per cent in the final quarter of last year following
the reimposition of stamp duty on house purchases and Britain's exit from
the exchange rate mechanism, Halifax Building Society said yesterday.
Halifax, the UK's largest building society, said in its quarterly index that
prices fell much faster in the last quarter than in the previous two. It
said much of the fall came in September as buyers' confidence was damaged by
the devaluation and the reimposition of stamp duty.
The biggest quarterly fall came in the East Midlands, where house prices
fell by 7 per cent. In the south-east, prices fell 5.9 per cent, taking the
fall in the average house price in the region to Pounds 31,800 in the past
three years.
In the year to December, UK house prices fell 7.8 per cent on average,
compared with a fall of 3.5 per cent in the same period of 1991 and a rise
of 0.5 per cent in 1990. The peak of house prices nationally was in July
1989.
The Halifax said house prices in East Anglia were now almost a third down on
the region's peak level in the fourth quarter of 1988, while prices in the
rest of the south had fallen to between 25 per cent and 30 per cent below
the peak.
The society said that although the housing market remained weak in the
fourth quarter, there had been evidence of more interest towards the end of
the year as prices became more affordable.
It said the increase in interest should be reflected in higher numbers of
house purchases this year, which would also be boosted by a more general
increase in confidence as the economy started to grow again.
It predicted that house prices would stabilise in the spring and then show
some increase in the second half of the year, giving way to a sustained
recovery next year.
The society's Halifax Property Services estate agency subsidiary said that
most agents had been 'pleasantly surprised' by business in December.
</TEXT>
