<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Safety mechanisms at Sizewell B n-power station may need
strengthening
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAFETY mechanisms at the Sizewell B nuclear power station in Suffolk might
need strengthening because of doubts over the efficiency of a computerised
fault-detection system, according to the British Computer Society, David
Green writes.
The primary protection system for the plant, which is due to start
generating electricity next year, involves 300 microprocessors and 98,000
lines of computer code.
The society says it doubts whether the existing programme of testing will
prove the efficiency of the system because of its complexity and it is
suggesting that either the testing programme or the secondary protection
system should be enhanced.
The society has made seven recommendations it wants Nuclear Electric, the
state-owned nuclear power generator, to carry out before the Nuclear
Installations Inspectorate approves the system. Nuclear Electric said
yesterday that the existing test programme was capable of demonstrating the
efficiency of the primary system and there would be no need to enhance the
secondary system.
