<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / West Midlands business confidence at new low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEWER West Midlands companies expect to take on more workers over the next
six months than at any time since the start of the recession, a survey of
1,200 businesses has disclosed.
The survey, by Wolverhampton and Warwick business schools and accountants
Price Waterhouse, published today, shows a sharp drop in business confidence
and a marked change in corporate attitudes towards government policy.
Concern about keeping down inflation has been replaced by estimates for
increased government expenditure coupled with lower interest rates to
provide new economic impetus.
Expectations for jobs go together with gloomy predictions about business
conditions. The latest survey shows that 56 per cent of companies expect
conditions to deteriorate over the next six months. Only 13 per cent expect
them to improve.
A third of companies expected to take on more labour last summer: that
proportion has dropped to 16 per cent. Over the past six months, 45 per cent
of companies have reduced their workforce, more than three times as many as
had expected to do during the summer.
Manufacturing was affected worst by the recession in its early stages, while
services remained buoyant.
Now, the survey says: 'The service sector is starting to experience the
employment shedding which has been taking place in the manufactur-ing sector
for some time.'
Recent analysis of official figures by the West Midlands Enterprise Board
showed that people out of work for more than a year made up 40 per cent of
the total jobless in Birmingham, the Black Country and Coventry.
The West Midlands Business Survey, Winter 1992-93. Wolverhampton Business
School, Wolverhampton University, Compton Park, Compton Road West,
Wolverhampton WV3 9DX. Summaries free, full copy Pounds 75.
