<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / US warning as Iraq taunts allies: Missile alert and third
incursion into Kuwait prompt threats from west
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US delivered a strong warning to Iraq yesterday over its tactic of
'going to the brink' as President Saddam Hussein continued to taunt the
United Nations and western allies.
The threat to Baghdad was echoed last night by the president of the UN
Security Council, Mr Yoshio Hatano of Japan, who said after a meeting with
Iraq's ambassador to the UN that he was losing his patience.
The Iraqi ambassador, Mr Nizar Hamdoon, said after handing over a letter to
Mr Hatano that Baghdad wanted to defuse the crisis by discussing a range of
issues with the Security Council.
However, Baghdad had no specific proposals and Mr Hatano said there had been
no mention at the meeting of an intention to open a dialogue.
Earlier yesterday, Mr Saddam changed the status of surface-to-air missiles
to operational in the northern air exclusion zone and, for the third
consecutive day, sent men across the border into Kuwait.
General John Shalikashvili, US supreme allied commander of Nato forces in
Europe, described Iraq's behaviour over the past few days as brinkmanship.
He warned that Baghdad could provoke a 'dangerous accident' by changing the
status of SA-2 and SA-3 missiles north of the 36th parallel where only
non-operational missiles are allowed.
Mr Robert Gates, the CIA director, said on Monday that Iraq had resumed
moving missiles in and out of the southern no-fly zone.
Mr Hamdoon said he was worried about a US attack but saw no way to prevent
such action.
Iraqi had also ignored the Security Council's condemnation on Monday of
incursions across the newly demarcated border into Kuwait. Mr Hatano said he
had told Mr Hamdoon that, in view of this condemnation, the council took
'very seriously' the continued removal yesterday by about 150 Iraqis of
warehouses and equipment near the port of Umm Qasr.
The UN has demanded the return of missiles and other military equipment
removed by 500 Iraqis from four weapons bunkers on Sunday.
In Britain, Downing Street said its impatience with Iraq was growing and
that further defiance of UN resolutions would be met by 'whatever action is
deemed necessary - and that includes military action'.
Officials recognise that Iraq is testing the UK, US and other allies with
small-scale incursions into Kuwait. But Downing Street signalled that any
reaction need not be proportionate to individual violations and could
reflect the cumulative impact of a succession of 'flea-bites'.
Mr Marlin Fitzwater, White House spokesman, repeated that the Iraqis would
get no further warnings. 'They cannot continue to violate UN resolutions and
there is a clear pattern to the violation, whether it is missiles or these
raids into warehouses, or other actions they have taken. It remains to be
seen what may come of that but, as we said, there will be no warnings.'
Mr Bob Hall, a Pentagon spokesman, said the US had the ability to take
action, if called upon to do so.
Newspapers in Baghdad said that western military forces would not deter Iraq
from challenging the restrictions imposed by the allies.
The two no-fly zones were created by the allies in the aftermath of the Gulf
war. The zone north of the 36th parallel was set up in 1991 to protect the
Kurdish population.
This was followed last August by one south of the 32nd parallel designed to
give the Shia population some relief against attacks by Baghdad forces
seeking to quell the remnants of the 1991 rebellion.
</TEXT>
