<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / UK Company News: Jacques Vert back in the black
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOLLOWING reversion to its core activities, Jacques Vert, the women's
fashion wear group, returned to the black and the dividend list in the six
months to October 24, though Mr Jack Cynamon and Mr Alan Green, joint
chairmen, said that 'a level of concern must be expressed as to prospects in
the immediate future'.
Mr Malcolm Heald, finance director since April, said the group had had a
good August and first half of September, but that there had been 'a 30 per
cent dive in sales between Black Wednesday and Christmas'. The first week of
the current sale had been good, he said, but the second had fallen off.
Pre-tax profits in the half were Pounds 186,000 (losses Pounds 125,000).
Turnover slipped by Pounds 700,000 to Pounds 19m, though the cost of sales
fell more steeply to Pounds 10.5m (Pounds 11.9m), giving gross profits up at
Pounds 8.55m (Pounds 7.78m).
Gearing was cut from 79 to 49.7 per cent through the reduction of stocks and
improved debtor collection. Net bank overdrafts at October 25 were down at
Pounds 3.9m (Pounds 6.11m on April 25), resulting in interest payable
falling to Pounds 304,000 (Pounds 402,000).
Below the line a tax credit of Pounds 200,000 (Pounds 48,000) eased the
board's decision to pay an interim dividend of 1p, according to Mr Heald.
Last time the interim was 2p, though the final was passed. Earnings were
4.2p (losses 0.8p) per share.
On the retail side - 10 per cent of the group's business - the number of
concessions rose from five in July to 25 in October, 32 now and, said Mr
Heald, '36 by the end of the week if all goes well'.
JV Plus, the line for larger women, continued to expand, the Grace
collection was launched, while Alain Cannelle was closed, the 51 per cent
stake in L'Anglaise was sold, and Mr Ben de Lisi bought out Vert's share of
their joint venture.
</TEXT>
