<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / Foreign Exchanges: Modest gain for dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR appreciated about  1/2 pfennig against the D-Mark in European
trading yesterday, but was pushed down again after Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the US
Treasury Secretary Designate, said the US had to reassert leadership in the
Group of Seven leading industrial nations, writes James Blitz.
Mr Bentsen may have depressed the US currency at his nomination hearings,
because his statement gave some strength to recent speculation that the G7
might act to put a cap on the recent rise in the dollar at a time when the
US is trying to boost its trade position.
At the start of European trading, the dollar made modest headway against the
German currency, partly due to the relative calm in the exchange rate
mechanism. The US unit peaked at DM1.6350 in London, also helped by
continuing tensions in the Middle East, which tend to be positive for the
dollar.
However, an analyst sugg-ested that the dollar will probably be confined to
tight range-trading in the run-up to Mr Bill Clinton's inaugur-ation as US
President later this month. There is growing uncertainty as to whether Mr
Clinton will announce a major fiscal package at the start of his presidency
to stimulate the economy.
The US currency's recent gains had partly been the result of expectations
that a fiscal stimulus would bring higher US interest rates, but recent
signs of strength in the US economy are starting to undermine this view.
The dollar ended in London slightly firmer at DM1.6320 compared with a
previous close of DM1.6305. It finished unchanged from the London level in
New York at DM1.6320.
The D-Mark again showed little new strength inside the European exchange
rate mechanism. The French franc rose to a six-week high against the German
currency, helped by news that France's inflation rate was at its lowest
level since 1956.
With the year-on-year inflation level down to 2.0 per cent, the franc moved
as high as FFr3.3924 per D-Mark, a point not seen since the end of November.
However, the currency later lost some ground to the D-Mark, finishing at
FFr3.395, up  1/2 centime on balance. An analyst pointed out that the low
inflation figure makes short-term interest rates in France, which are still
between 11 and 12 per cent, look very punishing.
There was less tension surrounding the Irish punt, which traded above its
floors against the Belgian franc and Dutch guilder for the second day
running.
The only significant loser yesterday was sterling, which suffered a
2-pfennig fall against the German currency to close at DM2.5125. Speculative
selling orders from Scandinavia were cited as a factor behind the currency's
fall. After last week's 6-pfennig rally against the D-Mark, a technical
correction was to be expected.
</TEXT>
