<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / International Company News: European sports channels to
merge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO of Europe's satellite television sports channels, Eurosport and Screen
Sport are to merge.
The deal, signed yesterday, unites companies such as TF1, the French first
channel, Canal Plus, the French subscription channel, and ESPN, the US
sports channel subsidiary of Capital Cities/ABC.
Screen Sport was founded by W. H. Smith, the UK retailer and Mr Rupert
Murdoch's News International once had a 50 per cent stake in Eurosport.
The single channel which will be shown throughout Europe simultaneously on
Astra and Eutelsat II satellites will be known as Eurosport/The European
Sports Network. There will be simultaneous commentaries in German, English
and Dutch.
TF1 will have a 34 per cent stake with Canal Plus and ESPN each on 33 per
cent.
A French language version broadcast on the Telecom 2 satellite will have
about 700 hours of programming a year appealing to French viewers. There
will be a separate shareholding structure for the French channel with Canal
Plus owning 34 per cent, TF1 31 per cent, Generale D'Image 25 per cent and
ESPN with 10 per cent.
The new channel will concentrate on sports such as football, tennis,
athletics, Formula 1, boxing and golf.
</TEXT>
