FT  13 JAN 93 / International Company News: Mellon Bank net profits soar 56%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MELLON BANK of Pittsburgh reported a 56 per cent jump in its full-year 1992
net profits, to Dollars 437m. Earnings per share for 1992 were Dollars 6.96,
against Dollars 4.66 in 1991. Fourth-quarter net income was 46 per cent
higher at Dollars 105m, or Dollars 1.62 a share, against Dollars 1.11 in
1991.
Mr Frank Cahouet, chairman and chief executive, said the bank's credit
quality improved during 1992, a year that saw the acquisition of The Boston
Company and 27 branches from Meritor, the former savings bank.
The fourth quarter saw 17 per cent higher net interest income of Dollars
301m and a 21 per cent rise in fee income to Dollars 228m. Bad debt
provisions were Dollars 35m, against Dollars 75m in the same quarter of
1991. For 1992, Mellon's bad debt provisions were Dollars 185m, against
Dollars 250m.
