<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / International Company News: KIO bid to sell Ebro stake runs
into difficulties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A BID by the Kuwait Investment Office to sell its controlling stake in the
profitable domestic food company Ebro ran into difficulties yesterday when
Mr Javier de la Rosa, the KIO's former chief Spanish executive, threatened
to block the deal.
Mr de la Rosa, who owns 12 per cent of Ebro and is at the centre of a
lawsuit over the KIO's troubled investment in Spain, issued a writ claiming
he hadthe right to buy the 36 per cent stake in Ebro.
Grupo Torras, the KIO's Spanish holding company which applied for
receivership last month claiming debts of Dollars 1.5bn and losses of
Dollars 4bn, has awarded the mandate to sell its Ebro stake to Credit Suisse
First Boston and hopes to realise more than Dollars 340m from its disposal.
A spokesman for Mr de la Rosa said the Barcelona-based financier had
obtained a written agreement from Torras in April last year for a first
option on its stake in the food company.
Mr de la Rosa, who was the architect of the Ebro stake, severed his links
with the KIO in May last year when new management took over at the KIO's
London's headquarters and at Torras.
Torras said: 'de la Rosa's writ cannot be considered legal.' According to
Torras, Mr de la Rosa's right over the stake was agreed between him and Mr
Jorge Nunez, then Torras's managing director. The agreement came days before
both men severed links with the KIO, Torras claimed.
Last Friday, Torras initiated criminal proceedings against Mr de la Rosa and
six other former Torras and KIO executives, including Mr Nunez, alleging
that they had committed financial irregularities which had involved Torras
in losses of more than Dollars 860m.
Most of Torras's shareholding in Ebro is pledged to creditor banks as
collateral for outstanding loans.
The main creditors, Bank of America, Chase Manhattan, Sumitomo and Spain's
Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, will have to wait for three to four for Credit Suisse
to conduct due diligence of Torras's stake in Ebro.
The Torras equity is worth about Dollars 200m at market prices because
Ebro's share value has been penalised by Torras's difficulties as well as
the market depression. Independent analysts put the value of a controlling
stake in Ebro at close to twice that amount.
It is not clear whether the Spanish government will allow Ebro to be
acquired by a non-Spanish company. The company, the biggest food group in
Spain, controls 54 per cent of the domestic sugar market and is held to be
Europe's leading rice producer.
</TEXT>
