<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Sharp Dow fall amid Gulf
fears is recouped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
LATE BUYING helped US share prices recover from large losses yesterday at
the end of a volatile session, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 1.89 on balance at
3,264.64. Having spent all morning no more than 5 points above or below
Monday's close, the Dow plunged more than 20 points in mid-afternoon before
retrieving all of its loss in the final 30 minutes of trading.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 moved in similar fashion,
ending a net 0.09 firmer at 431.04, while the American SE composite finished
0.83 off at 396.41 and the Nasdaq composite down 2.95 at 679.45. Volume on
the New York SE amounted to a heavy 239.4m shares.
News that Iraqis had entered Kuwait for the third time increased tension in
the Middle East. It also made investors even more cautious about buying
stocks ahead of what might turn out to be a resumption of hostilities in the
Gulf.
Uncertainty about the direction of domestic economic policy also contributed
to the market's lack of direction. Senator Lloyd Bentsen, the treasury
secretary designate, appeared before Congressional hearings yesterday but
provided few specific details on the likely policies of the Clinton
administration.
Among individual stocks, Chrysler dropped Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 34 5/8 in
volume of 2.8m shares as investors reacted to the news released late on
Monday that the financially stretched car manufacturer plans to bolster its
balance sheet by raising nearly Dollars 1.5bn through an international
offering of shares.
Elsewhere in the auto sector, Ford eased Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 45 and
General Motors held firm at Dollars 34 1/4 , largely untroubled by a report
from brokerage house SG Warburg which said Ford has been gaining market
share at GM's expense.
IBM continued to regain some of the ground lost over recent weeks. After
hitting a low last week of Dollars 45 7/8 , the stock has since risen
steadily. Yesterday it added Dollars 1 at Dollars 48 3/4 in busy trading.
The first batch of 1992 fourth-quarter earnings reports trickled in
yesterday, with Paramount softening Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 42 3/4 in spite
of news of a 22 per cent jump in the entertainment group's final quarter net
income to Dollars 110.2m.
Investors appeared equally unimpressed with record earnings from the Federal
National Mortgage Association, which reported an 18 per cent rise in
October-to-December profits to Dollars 426.4m, but saw its share price edge
Dollars  3/8 lower to Dollars 77 1/8 .
On the Nasdaq market, Rexon weakened Dollars 1 to Dollars 8 and Marcam
plunged Dollars 5 3/4 to Dollars 21 1/4 after the two companies issued
profits warnings.
Canada
TORONTO ended marginally firmer, lifted by a recovery in Canada's heavily
weighted gold shares and strength in the utilities sector due to a jump in
the shares of BCE Inc. Some of the smaller oil and gas issues also found
favour.
The TSE 300 index gained 4.4 at 3,314.5 but declines held an edge over
advances by 312 to 298 after volume of 49.2m shares valued at CDollars 357m.
BCE jumped after Bear Stearns initiated coverage on the company with a buy
recommendation. Strength in BCE, up CDollars 1 3/8 at CDollars 42 1/4 on
749,058 shares, boosted Northern Telecom, which is 52.6 per cent owned by
BCE. Nortel gained CDollars 1 1/4 at CDollars 53 1/4 .
</TEXT>
