<DATE>930112
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / London Stock Exchange: Cash call worries hurt CU
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO and PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPOSITE insurer Commercial Union fell 16 to 618p on turnover of 2.8m
shares amid renewed speculation that the company might be considering a
rights issue.
Analysts said a cash call by Commercial Union was possible given its aim for
growth in new business, the general pressure on margins and the recent rise
in its share price to an all-time high of 644p. In 1992, CU announced Pounds
100m preference share placings.
Both Kleinwort Benson and Credit Lyonnais Laing were reinforcing their view
that the stock was overvalued. Kleinwort's insurance analyst said the shares
were at an 8 per cent premium to net asset value at the start of trading
yesterday, and he also cited weekend press comment on the possibility of
impending rights issues.
Elsewhere in the sector, General Accident lost 16 at 558p and Sun Alliance
fell 7 to 351p. Royal Insurance, which is particularly in need of extra
cash, was 8 lower at 283p.
HSBC supported
A strong overnight performance by Hong Kong's Hang Seng index prompted HSBC
Holdings to buck the dreary trend in London and the shares received further
support from a recommendation by Robert Fleming Securities.
Fleming published a buy note arguing that the bank will produce profits of
Pounds 1.6bn in 1992 and Pounds 2.2bn in 1993. It also announced a Pounds
131.8m warrant issue. HSBC ordinaries were 10 higher at one stage and closed
3 up at 519p. The Hong Kong registered added 1 1/2 at 497 1/2 p and combined
turnover was 11m shares.
Institutions have taken additional heart from comments on Friday by Chinese
leaders on the Sino-British row over Hong Kong's plans for political reform.
Cable and Wireless, which is also heavily influenced by market activity in
Hong Kong, gained a penny at 708p. However, Standard Chartered, one of the
Footsie's best performers in recent months, shed 9 to 581p on profit-taking.
Alexon raided
Further evidence of the fragile state of the consumer recovery was shown
with a bear raid on Alexon ahead of an expected cautious trading statement
this week. Shares in the clothes retailer dived sharply as the market
opened, losing around 20 per cent of their value before steadying. They
closed at 82p, a fall of 17 on the day. The drop was at first blamed on a
downgrade by Morgan Stanley, but the broker later denied this.
If the bears are to be believed, Alexon will join a growing list of
retailers to report flat pre-Christmas sales - taking the shine from earlier
talk that the much-heralded consumer recovery was gathering pace. Analysts
said they expected Alexon to reveal no improvement at its Dash chain, where
sales had been under pressure, resulting in downgrades last quarter.
Nervousness over the strength of the retail revival also undermined the
stores sector. Ratners, due to announce the level of its Christmas sales
shortly, ran into the bearish sentiment and the shares slipped 1 1/2 to 11
3/4 p on turnover of 18m. So too did Body Shop, off 10 at 164p.
The hangover from last week's trading statement from Boots, in which the
retailer revealed poor sales at its Do It All subsidiary, continued.
Analysts reported that the DIY group's owners - Boots and WH Smith - were
hinting that losses this year could reach Pounds 30m, double most market
estimates. This comes on top of reports that the two groups will need to
invest a further Pounds 15m into Do It All to fund a new distribution
centre. Boots fell 10 to 500p and WH Smith 'A' 13 to 456p.
A number of brokers advised profit-taking in Dixons, whose shares have
surged in post-Christmas trading on reports of strong computer games sales
and buoyant US electronics demand. However, neither of these factors
satisfied BZW, which said Dixons' US subsidiary Silo is still in
difficulties and the effect of sterling devaluation has still to be felt.
Nomura was also negative, arguing that the shares had run too far. Yesterday
they fell 12 to 262p.
Conglomerate Hanson held steady among weak internationally traded stocks on
reports that it had swapped its US gold mining operations for the coal
business of railroads and minerals group Santa Fe Pacific.
If it proceeds, the swap would make Hanson the world's second largest
privately held coal producer, while placing Santa Fe among the top 10 US
gold producers. The stock also received some support ahead of a presentation
to analysts in New York yesterday. Hanson shares eased 1 1/2 to 236p.
Profit forecast upgrades for BAT Industries by Hoare Govett failed to
counter the impact of a weaker dollar and the shares fell 12 to 968p. Hoare
has raised its figure for the year to March 10 by Pounds 60m to Pounds
1.63bn and that for the following year by Pounds 35m to Pounds 2.175bn. The
house is basing its reassessment on a better than expected output from the
tobacco side and a faster turnround for Eagle Star.
Among other dollar stocks, Reuters Holdings receded 14 to 1388p in spite of
announcing the launch of a new real time service for global money and
capital markets.
Shell lost 10 to 533p after a good run as investors switched into Royal
Dutch.
Glaxo and SmithKline Beecham stood out firmly in a weak market as investors
took advantage of last week's price decline among big pharmaceutical
companies. A 1 per cent rise in Merck in New York also helped the shares.
Salomon Brothers was heavily on the bid again. Glaxo rose 8 to 740p and
SmithKline a penny to 469p in the 'A's and 3 to 412p in the Units.
Wellcome was 9 lower at 925p, however, following weekend press reports of
patent issues surrounding its two leading drugs. AAH retreated 18 to 597p
after a recent run. Broker Hoare Govett, although still a buyer of the
shares, shaved its forecasts.
The decision by Associated British Foods not to proceed with the purchase of
a US sugar processing group disappointed some in the market and the shares
fell 8 to 505p. Strong second line stocks from last week met profit-taking.
Among these, Booker fell 12 to 415p, Unigate 10 to 320p and Hillsdown, which
is hosting a series of institutional meetings this week, 10 to 134p.
Iceland Frozen Foods slipped 13 1/2 to 651p. Kleinwort Benson was said to
have moved from a buy to a hold position.
Rights issue talk again stalked Stakis and the hotel and casino group lost 3
to 41p.
Profit-taking hit the engineering sector, which has outperformed the market
by around 15 per cent over the past month. Siebe gave up 21 at 430p, further
affected by vague talk of a rights issue, while IMI dipped 12 to 266p.
Vickers 8 to 114p, Simon Engineering 9 to 110p and Meggitt 5 to 92p.
Reports of a US investigation into a subsidiary hurt TI Group and the shares
weakened 10 to 298p. However, Mr Paul Compton at Credit Lyonnais Laing said:
'Given that the contract under investigation is only worth Pounds 1m, I
think the fall has been overdone.'
Smiths Industries eased 4 to 376p, with BZW shifting its recommendation from
buy to hold. However, the house stressed it was a long-term supporter of the
stock.
Although Tomkins reported a 7.6 per cent improvement in interim figures to
Pounds 47.1m, the meeting with analysts disappointed and the shares fell 11
to 246p in trade of 3.6m.
Trafalgar House softened 2 to 87p after the chairman told the annual meeting
he foresaw no upturn in 1993.
Profit-taking and switching sent BICC down 8 to 334p. Dealers reported
switching into Delta, steady at 435p.
A downgrading in Rugby took the shine off the building materials sector. The
shares retreated 15 to 219p and pulled down Blue Circle 9 to 196p in their
wake.
USM-quoted aromatic oils company Treatt advanced 10 to 118p on healthy
annual profits.
Chemicals group Laporte rallied 4 to 587p following its bid for Evode, a
penny firmer at 120p, as a buy note from Williams de Broe landed on clients'
desks.
