<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / International Company News: Banesto sells corporate loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANCO Espanol de Credito (Banesto) yesterday became the first bank in
continental Europe to remove corporate loans from its balance sheet through
securitisation.
Securitisation allows banks or companies to repackage assets and sell them
to investors, thus removing these assets from their balance sheets for
accounting purposes, and, in the case of banks, reducing the amount of
capital they need to hold.
This is the latest innovative financing used by Spanish banks to raise new
capital, following a series of preferred share offerings and subordinated
debt placements.
Banesto has set up a Dollars 1bn Euro-commercial paper programme, backed by
loans to Spanish companies. The first Dollars 30m tranche of one-month
commercial paper, backed by a three-year loan, was issued under the
programme yesterday. As the commercial paper matures, more paper is issued
throughout the life of the underlying loan. In case no investor can be found
for the new paper, a liquidity facility is provided by JP Morgan, the
arranger of the programme.
According to JP Morgan, the structure allows Banesto to fund the loans at a
cost below the London interbank offered rate, which is cheaper than their
normal cost of funds.
Loans to companies are considered the most difficult assets to securitise.
Because of their large size, risk is much more concentrated than in the
securitisation of, for example, mortgages. Unlike consumer loans, they are
individually negotiated transactions.
A number of UK banks, which have been experiencing difficulties in the
corporate loan market during the recession, have been eyeing the structure.
</TEXT>
