<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Government urged to look at ACT issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CORPORATE lobbyists are again pressing the government to find at least a
partial solution to the problem of surplus advance corporation tax before
the Budget this spring.
They hope that Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, will go further than last
year's budget speech when he merely promised to look at the issue. Since
then no changes have been made.
In aggregate, companies are estimated to be paying Pounds 500m a year too
much in tax because their mainstream corporation tax bill is too low to
offset fully the ACT paid on their dividends.
However, the government is expected to be reluctant to agree to any solution
that would reduce revenues given the size of the budget deficit.
The ACT issue is regarded by many as a structural rather than a cyclical
problem as UK companies expand abroad and earn a higher proportion of
profits internationally.
UK companies argue that they are increasingly at a disadvantage to rivals
based elsewhere, as the ACT system effectively penalises companies which pay
dividends out of non-UK profits. One British finance director said: 'If the
government wants industry to have a level playing field against
international companies then it would be a great help to have some relief
from ACT.'
There is a fear that companies, whose earnings are depressed because of high
tax charges caused by unrelieved ACT, will find it more expensive to raise
new equity capital needed to finance expansion. Another concern is that ACT
deters international holding companies from setting up in the UK.
Details, Page 21
</TEXT>
